&lt;div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"&gt;&lt;h3 id="Wildlife"&gt;Wildlife&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;span class="mw-editsection"&gt;&lt;span class="mw-editsection-bracket"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="/w/index.php?title=Tadasu_no_Mori&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Wildlife"&gt;&lt;span&gt;edit&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="mw-editsection-bracket"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not many large mammals have been observed in Tadasu No Mori. In the 1960s there were sightings of the Japanese Squirrel (Sciurus lis), however, in recent years the squirrel's presence has vanished. In terms of birds, the Brown Hawk-Owl (Ninox scutulata), a migratory bird which generally spends winters in South East Asia, was observed on three instances nesting within hollow trees during a 2002 survey of Tadasu No Mori. Since elm trees often form hollow cavities, Tadasu No Mori is considered a suitable habitat for such birds.
&lt;/p&gt;
